{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473228"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2043"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2043"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.6,0.06,0.07,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2043"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92993"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2043"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2043"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76346"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1031"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31924"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44066"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92993"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 4-year-old boy is brought to his general practitioner because his parents are concerned about his rebellious behaviour during the past year. They explain that the boy often ignores them whenever they call him. He also has increasing episodes of unprovoked crying and screaming. His parents express concern over his learning in kindergarten and cooperation with the teachers. During kindergarten the child does not listen to the teacher when instructions are given, even as the teacher sits next to him and tries to talk to him. He maintains eye contact with the teacher, but does not respond to such instructions. He is still able to participate in group activities with no difficulty. In terms of his development, he started walking at the age of 10 \u00bd months and is only able to speak in two-word phrases. He often mispronounces words as well. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the child looks well and healthy and within his normal growth percentile. He appears chirpy and maintains eye contact when spoken to. However, he does not respond to instructions when engaged in play.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Opposition defiant disorder","Hearing impairment","Selective mutism","Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder","Autism spectrum disorder"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question challenges the reader\u2019s knowledge on child psychiatry as well as the developmental milestones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUndetected \u003Cstrong\u003Ehearing impairments\u003C/strong\u003E can cause delays in speech, language and cognitive development. In this case, the patient presented with attention difficulties on the surface. He has challenges understanding instructions when directly spoken to, mispronunciation of words and delayed development. At four years of age, this patient should be able to speak in at least 4-word sentences. His mispronunciation of words is largely due to poor speech discernment from his hearing and this has affected his ability to learn correct pronunciation. Often, a child with hearing impairments may express frustration in the form of screaming and crying. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOpposition defiant disorder (ODD) may present with difficulties with school, lack of cooperation with authority, defiance against instructions given to them. Children with ODD may also express outburst of anger. These symptoms may present similarly - however, there is a lack of ODD behaviours such as revenge-seeking patterns, intense aggression towards parents or school teachers and out-of-proportionate arguing. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003ESelective mutism is a childhood anxiety disorder characterised by a refusal to speak in certain situations i.e. in school, while the child may be perfectly comfortable to speak at home or with friends. This often presents with social phobia. Selective mutism is less likely in this child as he does not fail to speak in public environments and does not show any signs of childhood anxiety. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EAttention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) presents with symptoms of inattention and impulsivity as seen in this child\u2019s unprovoked screaming and crying. However, delayed development \u2013 in particular language delay \u2013 is not common in ADHD. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EAutism may present with impaired language development and deficits in social interactions and communication at home and school. However, this child lacks key characteristic features of autism such as poor eye contact, repetitive and stereotyped patterns of behaviour. This child seems to be able to participate with group activities, showing adequate social cues and emotional behaviour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hearing impairments can cause delays in speech, language and cognitive development."],"references":["Mayes S, Calhoun S, Crowell E. Learning Disabilities and ADHD. Journal of Learning Disabilities. 2000;33(5):417-424.","McInerny T. Children Who Have Difficulty in School: A Primary Pediatrician\u0027s Approach. Pediatrics in Review. 1995;16(9):325-332.","American Psychiatric Association. Language disorder. In: Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fifth Edition, American Psychiatric Association, Arlington, VA 2013. p.42."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76346"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2043"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76346"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T12:29:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T12:29:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2043"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92993"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"